title: For Sale:  Radom 1976 polish P-64
postcontent:
SUPPLY IS BECOMING SCARCE. In Very Good condition. The P-64 pistol (official designation 9 mm pistolet wz. 1964) was developed in Poland during late 1950s and early 1960s, as a compact and lightweight replacement for Tokarev TT pistols, manufactured in Poland under soviet license. Following the Soviet road, Poland replaced the powerful 7.62x25mm ammunition with less powerful, but still effective 9x18 Makarov ammunition. P-64 has been used by both Polish military and police, and still can be found in holsters of some Polish police officers. In military service it has been superseded in mid-1980s by the P-83 pistol. The P-64 was small and light enough for a pocket or a concealed carry sidearm. P-64 is a blowback operated, semi-automatic weapon, made almost entirely of steel. P-64 is hammer fired, with double-action trigger and decocking safety, mounted at the left side of the slide. Safety features also include loaded chamber indicator in the form of a small pin, which protrudes from the back of the slide, above the hammer, when chamber is loaded with cartridge. Trigger guard is a separate unit, which is hinged to the frame and served as a disassembly lever when pulled down. Single stack magazine contains only 6 rounds, and magazine release catch is located at the bottom of the grip. Perfect for licensed concealment carry. 

COMES WITH 2 EXTRA MAGS,HOLSTER AND 600 ROUNDS BROWNBEAR FMJ AND 20 CORBON HP. Type: Double Action Calibers: 9x18 Makarov Weight unloaded: 635 g Length: 155 mm Barrel length: 85 mm Capacity: 6 rounds

title: For Sale:  COLT - COMBAT COMMANDER 9mm -- Series 70
postcontent: Here's a very nice Colt pistol! This is a Series 70 Combat Commander. Chambered for the 9mm Parabellum and featuring full steel construction, this pistol was manufactured in about 1979 and remains in excellent condition. The original blue finish rates about 98-99% overall with only a few very minor handling marks. There is no rust or any pitting. The original arched mainspring housing has been replaced with a flat checkered steel unit but the balance of the pistol appears all original. The checkered walnut grips have gold Colt medallions and are excellent without any chips, cracks or dings. The mechanics are in perfect working order and the bore is excellent, bright and sharp. title: For Sale:  Antique Colts
postcontent: Colt Burgess Rifle .44-40. A Full octagon barrel and full length magazine tube which holds 15 rounds. The barrel and tube have developed an eye appealing even light chocolate brown patina. The barrel shows silvering on edges and scattered light pitting. Both have scattered light rust specks and a few nicks and scratches. Lettering on top barrel flat crisp including patent dates. The receiver retains about 75% original bright blue with silvering on edges and light rust specks and light pitting towards the front. Bright nitre on loading gate and trigger. Strong blue remains on bottom tang. Good case color on hammer and faded color on finger lever. Frame screw heads have very slight raised edges. Buttplate is gray with pitting on top. The stock is overall smooth with the buttstock showing no visible cracks and only a few light scattered indentations. The forend has lesser handling but does have a small worn chip on right side adjacent to cap. Made from 1883 to 1885, this levergun was part of Colt's plan to provide a well-rounded complement of firearms to the shooting public. Produced in caliber .44-40 in both carbine and rifle form, just a little over 6,000 were ever produced. According to stories when Colt tooled up to produce this levergun, Winchester tooled up and made a few revolvers. Winchester then told Colt they were thinking of going into the handgun business, especially if Colt was going to go into the levergun business! Shortly thereafter Colt dropped the Burgess and Winchester made no more handguns.
